Ferrovial, Fiat, Novartis, Shell, Total: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-04-11T00:38:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-11/ferrovial-fiat-novartis-shell-total-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.3 percent to 281.68. The
Stoxx 50 Index increased 0.3 percent to 2,647.95. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, gained 0.7
percent to 2,984.66.  Allied Irish Banks Plc (ALBK)  : The Dublin-based,
government-controlled lender may shed almost 2,000 jobs, the
Sunday Times said, without citing anyone. The bank will scale
down its loan portfolio by as much as 19 billion euros ($27.5
billion) even as it keeps First Trust Bank, the bank’s Northern
Irish unit, the newspaper said. The stock fell 6.4 percent to
0.28 euros.  Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena SpA (BMPS)  :  Italy ’s
third-biggest bank may call a board meeting this week to approve
a 2 billion euro rights offering, two people familiar with the
situation said. The stock climbed 1.5 percent to 93.1 cents.  Air Berlin Plc (AB1)  (AB1 GY):  Germany ’s second-largest airline
has appointed Barbara Cassani and Saad Hammad as top managers to
help it return to profit,  Financial Times Deutschland  reported,
citing Air Berlin Chief Executive Officer Joachim Hunold. Shares
of the German company advanced 1.3 percent to 3.15 euros.  Allied Irish Banks Plc (ALBK ID): The Dublin-based,
government-controlled lender may shed almost 2,000 jobs, the
Sunday Times said, without citing anyone. The bank will scale
down its loan portfolio by as much as 19 billion euros ($27.5
billion) even as it keeps First Trust Bank, the bank’s Northern
Irish unit, the newspaper said. The stock fell 6.4 percent to
0.28 euros.  BP Plc (BP/)  : The oil producer faces a showdown with
shareholders this week at its annual meeting after the
 Association of British Insurers  issued an “amber top” alert
over executive bonuses, the Observer reported.  Separately, BP Plc’s board may replace former Chief
Executive Officer  Tony Hayward  as a director of its 50 percent-
owned Moscow-based affiliate TNK-BP, the Sunday Telegraph
reported without saying where it got the information. The shares
rose 0.8 percent to 478.5 pence.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : The carmaker is “optimistic” its
joint offer for German engine maker Tognum AG will be accepted
by enough shareholders, and doesn’t plan to increase its offer,
Die Welt reported, citing Chief Financial Officer Bodo Uebber.
The stock declined 0.2 percent to 52.04 euros.  EDF Energies Nouvelles SA (EEN)  : Chairman Paris
Mouratoglou has agreed to sell his 25 percent stake in the
French renewable-energy company to Electricite de France SA (EDF
FP), which offered by buy out minority shareholders for about a
10 percent premium over the last traded price. The shares were
unchanged at 36.6 euros.  Eni SpA (ENI)  : Libyan unrest may cut Eni’s full-year
2011 production by 156,000 barrels a day,  Il Sole 24 Ore  said,
without saying where it got the information. The stock rose 1.1
percent to 17.72 euros.  Ferrovial SA (FER)  : The company’s Heathrow Airport
imposed a contract exempting itself from blame for airline
losses in cases such as December’s snowfall, the London-based
Times said. The stock rose 1.91 percent to 9.29 euros.  Fiat SpA (F)  : The Italian automaker that controls
Chrysler Group LLC is preparing to increase its stake in the
U.S. company to 30 percent from 25 percent as soon as this week,
two people familiar with the matter said.  Separately, Automotive News Europe said Alfa Romeo’s return
to the U.S. has been delayed by at least six months to mid-2013,
citing people with direct knowledge of the matter. The stock
fell 0.7 percent to 6.6 euros.  Intesa Sanpaolo SpA (ISP)  : Compagnia di San Paolo, the
biggest shareholder in Italy’s second-biggest bank, said it will
approve the bank’s proposal to sell new shares. The shares
dropped 1.1 percent to 2.26 euros.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : A report by the
Independent Commission on Banking due on April 11 will say that
the merger of Lloyds TSB and HBOS was a mistake which could be
partly reversed by the bank reducing its presence on U.K. high
streets, Sky News reported. The stock gained 0.5 percent to
62.16 pence.  Novartis AG (NOVN)  : The Swiss drugmaker plans to further
reduce its debt before making “large” acquisitions, Blick
said, citing Chairman Daniel Vasella. The shares dropped 0.8
percent to 50.75 francs.  Roche Holding AG (ROG)  : The world’s biggest maker of
cancer drugs must pay $2 million to a former user of its
Accutane acne drug who alleged the medicine destroyed her
intestinal system, a jury concluded. The stock fell 0.1 percent
to 133.8 francs.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  : Europe’s largest  oil
company  agreed to acquire a stake in Chevron Corp.’s proposed
A$20 billion ($21 billion) Wheatstone natural gas project in
 Western Australia . Shell climbed 1 percent to 26.06 euros.  Swatch Group AG (UHR)  : The strength of the franc cost
the world’s biggest watchmaker about 150 million francs ($165
million) in revenue in the first quarter, NZZ am Sonntag said,
citing Chief Executive Officer Nick Hayek in an interview. The
stock dropped 0.3 percent to 400.1 francs.  Total SA (FP)  : The French oil company is in exclusive
talks with private equity firm Klesch & Co. Ltd. for the sale in
its Lindsey refinery in the U.K. for as much as 2 billion pounds
($3.3 billion), the Sunday Telegraph said, without saying where
it got the information. The shares rose 0.7 percent to 43.15
euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
